<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-income-tax-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Income Tax I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Compute income tax using taxation table
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To break down real-world compensation profiles into algebraic sub-components (basic salary, allowances, tax exemptions) and discover how statutory baseline deductions shape taxable income.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into small collaborative teams. Direct them to work through the four introductory Case Studies sequentially. Ensure groups understand that currency translation between Kenyan Shillings and Kenya Pounds (<m>1 \;\text{K£} \; = \;\text{Ksh}\; 20</m>) requires dividing the Shilling total by <m>20</m>. When discussing Case Study <m>2</m>, guide learners to observe that the NSSF contribution acts as an allowable deduction, which physically shrinks the final taxable base. Emphasize that personal relief in Case Study <m>4</m> is a straight reduction applied to the gross tax liability, not to the income base itself.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>

            <p>
                <term>Work in Groups</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                In every economy, individuals earn income from employment. However, not all income earned is taken home because the government collects tax to fund public services such as roads, education, and healthcare.
            </p>

            <p>
                In this activity, learners investigate how income tax is computed from salaries, allowances, deductions, and reliefs.
            </p>

            <p>
                Identify different components that make up a worker's monthly income and discuss how these components affect the final amount received.
            </p>

            <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Income Component</cell>
                    <cell>Role in Salary Structure</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Basic salary</cell>
                    <cell>Primary earnings for work done</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Allowances</cell>
                    <cell>Additional income for services or conditions</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Deductions</cell>
                    <cell>Amounts removed before take-home pay</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>

            <p>
                <alert>Case Study 1:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                Mr. Barasa manages a local sustainable dairy farm and earns a monthly salary of Ksh <m>48,000</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                In groups, determine his annual income and convert it into Kenya Pounds (K£) given that <m>1 \text{ K£} = \text{Ksh } 20</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Case Study 2:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                Teacher Wanjiku is reviewing her monthly employment contract. It lists a basic salary of Ksh <m>35,000</m>, a house allowance of Ksh <m>12,000</m>, and a medical allowance of Ksh <m>3,000</m>. Before she is taxed, she must contribute Ksh <m>200</m> to the National Social Security Fund (NSSF).
            </p>

            <p>
                Work in Groups to determine her monthly taxable income.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Case Study 3:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                A clerk earns Ksh <m>10,000</m> taxable income. The tax rate for this bracket is <m>10\%</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                Determine the gross tax payable.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Case Study 4:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                 A worker calculates their gross tax and finds it comes to Ksh <m>4,500</m>. However, the government grants every Kenyan worker a financial discount called Personal Relief of Ksh <m>2,400</m> to ease the cost of living. Determine the actual Net Tax (PAYE) that will be deducted from the worker's payslip.
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>What happens to income before a worker receives it?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Why are allowances added to basic salary?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Why is relief deducted from gross tax?</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>How does tax affect the final income received by a worker?</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize sequential equations for individual income tax calculations and distinguish cleanly between pre-tax deductions and post-tax financial relief.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Use the results from Case Studies 1 through 4 to build a unified salary-to-tax workflow on the board. Show explicitly that allowances expand an individual's gross pay, whereas non-taxable statutory contributions like NSSF pull that value back down to produce the true taxable principal.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Pre-Tax vs. Post-Tax Distinction:</alert> Address a common point of confusion directly: point out that deductions (like NSSF) are subtracted from <em>gross income before</em> tax is calculated, whereas reliefs (like Personal Relief) are subtracted from the <em>gross tax amount after</em> the percentage rate is applied.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Currency Standardization:</alert> Reinforce that tax reference lookup tables are historically structured in Kenya Pounds (<m>\text{K£}</m>) either monthly or annually. Drill the conversion mechanism so that shifting between Ksh and K£ becomes an intuitive operational step before matching tax brackets.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->
     <insight>
        <p>
            Income tax is a compulsory contribution deducted from an individual's earnings based on their income structure.
        </p>

        <p>
            A worker's net income is built from:
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Income} = \amp\; \text{Basic Salary} + \text{Allowances} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Taxable Income} = \amp \; \text{Gross Income} - \text{Allowable Deductions} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Tax} = \amp \; \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Tax Rate} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Tax (PAYE)} = \amp \; \text{Gross Tax} - \text{Personal Relief} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Income} = \amp \; \text{Gross Income} - \text{PAYE} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            The key idea is that taxation reduces take-home pay, but the system is structured to ensure fairness through allowances and reliefs.
        </p>
     </insight>


    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr. Barasa earns a monthly salary of Ksh <m>48,000</m>. Calculate his annual income in Kenya Pounds (K£).
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Calculating the annual income 
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Annual Income}: \amp \; 48,000 \times 12 = \;\text{Ksh}\;576,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Income in (K£)}: \amp \; \frac{576000}{20} = \text{K£} 28,800</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A teacher has a basic salary of Ksh <m>35,000</m>, a house allowance of Ksh <m>12,000</m>, and a medical allowance of Ksh <m>3,000</m>. She contributes Ksh <m>200</m> to NSSF. Find her monthly taxable income.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Gross Income} \amp =\; \text{Basic salary} + \text{Allowances} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 35,000 + 12,000 + 3,000 = \text{Ksh}\; 50,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Taxable Income} \amp = \; \text{Gross tax} - \text{Deductions} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 50,000 - 200 = \text{Ksh} \;49,800 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A clerk earns Ksh <m>10,000</m> taxable income, calculate his gross tax given a tax bracket is Ksh <m>1 - 12,298</m> at a rate of <m>10\%</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We calculate the Gross tax
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Gross tax} \amp = \; \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Rate} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 10,000 \times \frac{10}{100} = \text{Ksh} \; 1,000 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                After calculating his tax, Esther finds his Gross Tax is Ksh <m>4,500</m>. If he is entitled to a Personal Relief of Ksh <m>2,400</m>, calculate his Net Tax (PAYE).
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Net Tax} \amp = \;\text{Gross tax} - \text{Relief} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 4,500 - 2,400 = \text{Ksh} \; 2,100 </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A manager earns a basic salary of K£ <m>1,500</m> per month. Calculate his annual income in Ksh.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                   <m>\text{Ksh} \; 360,000</m> 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A civil servant's gross monthly income is Ksh <m>64,000</m>. If his total tax less deductions amount to Ksh <m>1,080</m>, find his taxable income in K£ per month.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{K£}\; 3146</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The yearly tax rate for income between K£ <m>1 - 2,400</m> is <m>2</m> Ksh per £. John earns K£ <m>2,000</m> per year, calculate his Gross tax.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{Ksh} \; 4,000</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A officer's monthly gross tax is Ksh <m>7,200</m>. The individual is given a personal relief of Ksh <m>2,400</m> and an insurance relief of Ksh <m>600</m>. Calculate his PAYE.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>4,200</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Matrix for Income Tax Calculations</title>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>Struggling Learners (Support)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Provide highly guided instruction using structural templates that isolate one operation at a time: Gross Income <m>=</m> Basic Pay <m>+</m> Allowances. Use integer numbers to practice the <m>\div 20</m> currency transformation step on its own.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The teacher models individual extraction steps on the board. Provide worksheets with pre-labeled categories (Basic, Allowances, Deductions) so learners can easily organize numerical data from word problems before calculating.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>On-Level Learners (Core)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Learners independently extract income variables, handle currency conversions, and apply sequential formulas to determine taxable income and Net PAYE.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            They analyze realistic corporate and civil service salary scenarios, compute percentage-based gross tax rates within basic brackets, and apply monthly personal reliefs. Practice translating text-dense multi-tiered employment benefits into step-by-step arithmetic strings.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Extend problems to include reverse calculations, such as determining an employee's basic salary or gross income when given only their final net take-home pay and tax parameters.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Task learners with analyzing the economic implications of progressive tax rates versus flat tax rates. Have them investigate how moving up an income bracket affects an individual's net marginal return, and ask them to construct original contextual payslip scenarios for their peers to decode.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Teacher Execution Guidance</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Classroom Architecture:</alert> Cluster your struggling learners together near the front of the room. This layout allows you to verify their currency conversion steps (<m>\text{Ksh} \div 20</m>) quickly before they attempt bracket tax rates, while core and advanced groups work independently on the multi-tiered calculations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Strategic Peer Modeling:</alert> If a core learner completes the exercises early, pair them with a support group as a consultant. Having them explain the difference between a pre-tax deduction and a post-tax relief to a peer strengthens their own mastery of commercial vocabulary.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The "What If" Lever:</alert> When evaluating advanced groups, deepen their reasoning with a single question: <em>"If the government increases personal relief by Ksh <m>1,000</m>, does a low-income worker or a high-income worker see a larger percentage increase in their net take-home pay?"</em> This prompts immediate mathematical analysis of progressive tax systems.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
